00:03:08.800 --> 00:03:16.160
in with really great computational experience in other languages. So one thing that is important

00:03:16.160 --> 00:03:21.279
to know if you are trying to get unstuck with Python is that you can end up in situations called

00:03:21.279 --> 00:03:27.759
dependency hell. Dependency hell is a phrase that means you are trying to use two packages at the

00:03:27.759 --> 00:03:34.479
same time that have conflicting two packages that have conflicting dependencies. Maybe one package

00:03:34.479 --> 00:03:39.600
needs a version 1 of a dependency, and another package needs version 2, and so you literally

00:03:39.600 --> 00:03:45.919
cannot install them into the same environment to use together. This is different from the experience

00:03:45.919 --> 00:03:52.479
that many of us are used to coming from CRAN, because CRAN not only will make sure packages

00:03:52.479 --> 00:03:58.639
work in isolation, but CRAN actually tests all the packages together, and on any given day,

00:03:58.639 --> 00:04:04.320
if you try to install package A from CRAN and package B from CRAN, you can do that on any given

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:13.119
day. In Python, from PyPI, PyPI will say, okay, here's package A, here's package B. They have

00:04:13.119 --> 00:04:21.119
conflicting dependencies, and PyPI says, good luck. This is your problem to deal with.

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:28.720
Another thing that's unique about the Python dependency situation is that there is no default

00:04:28.720 --> 00:04:36.160
or built-in package manager, and this is different from ecosystems like JavaScript with NPM or the

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:42.399
Rust ecosystem with Cargo. There's no equivalent to this kind of thing in Python. Instead, instead

00:04:42.399 --> 00:04:49.200
of having one of these, Python has a whole bunch. If you've heard of things like Conda and poetry

00:04:49.200 --> 00:04:56.079
and PIP tools and PyM, these are all different tools in the package management space, but they

00:04:56.079 --> 00:05:01.920
don't all do the same thing. Instead, think of them as an overlapping Venn diagram of different

00:05:01.920 --> 00:05:08.000
kinds of tools that have a different perspective on what the important thing to do is. You can

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:12.640
actually use some of those things I just mentioned together at the same time to do different sort of

00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:18.640
pieces, whether it's dependency resolution or make a virtual environment. So ten years ago,

00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:25.279
I'm trying to get up and running, and my Python situation was a disaster. I was like, how can I

00:05:25.279 --> 00:05:31.359
not even install packages? This is bananas. I cannot believe how much trouble I'm having here.

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:38.880
I said this is a talk of good news, and I am really happy to be able to say that so this has

00:05:38.880 --> 00:05:46.720
been a long-running problem in the Python ecosystem, but as they keep making new tools, the newest sort

00:05:46.720 --> 00:05:52.799
of tools in this space, they're actually good. They're actually good. So the first tool that

00:05:52.799 --> 00:05:59.200
really made me sort of sit up and pay attention was a tool called PyM, and it is a great tool

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:04.959
for installing Python and making virtual environments, and I was like, wow, this is

00:06:04.959 --> 00:06:10.799
actually pleasant to use and works as I expect, but today what I would recommend now if you're

00:06:10.799 --> 00:06:17.760
trying to get going is a tool called UV. What's unique about UV is it is an all-in-one solution.

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:24.320
So it provides tooling for everything that you need to do in the package management space.

00:06:24.320 --> 00:06:29.839
It will do dependency resolution. It will install packages for you. It will help you make virtual

00:06:29.839 --> 00:06:36.799
environments. Like it will do all of it, and it is blazing fast. Now, I'm someone who

00:06:37.519 --> 00:06:43.040
like often performance is not the thing I care about most about the software that I'm using,

00:06:43.040 --> 00:06:51.040
but UV is so performant and so well-designed and pleasant to use that it reduces the pain

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:58.720
of Python environment management work to a level I honestly would not have believed you 10 years

00:06:58.720 --> 00:07:05.600
ago. Like it is truly so much improved. There are a lot of different ways you can use UV.

